  <h2 id="why-kanji-matters">Why Kanji Mastery Matters</h2>
  <p>Kanji is the single biggest challenge — and the single biggest reward — of learning Japanese. These Chinese-derived characters carry meaning in compact visual form, and mastering them unlocks the ability to read signs, menus, books, and websites in Japanese. Without kanji knowledge, you are functionally illiterate in Japan, unable to read train station names, restaurant menus, or product labels.</p>
  <p>The good news is that kanji learning follows a predictable curve. The first 200 characters feel overwhelming because everything is new. But as you learn more, patterns emerge: you start recognizing shared components, predicting readings, and guessing meanings of unfamiliar characters. By the time you reach 500 kanji, learning new ones becomes significantly easier because you are building on existing knowledge.</p>

