  <p>The key insight is that you do not need to learn all 2,136 jouyou kanji before Japanese becomes useful. Even 300 kanji — the JLPT N4 level — lets you read more than half the kanji in everyday text. Your goal should be steady, consistent progress rather than rushing to memorize everything at once.</p>

  <h2 id="radical-method">The Radical Decomposition Method</h2>
  <p>Kanji are not random drawings. Nearly every kanji is built from smaller components called <strong>radicals</strong> (部首). Learning these building blocks transforms kanji from mysterious symbols into logical combinations with predictable meanings. There are 214 classical radicals, but knowing about 50-60 common ones covers the vast majority of kanji you will encounter.</p>

  <h3>How Radicals Reveal Meaning</h3>
  <p>Most kanji contain a <strong>semantic radical</strong> that hints at the meaning category and a <strong>phonetic component</strong> that suggests the on'yomi reading. For example, every kanji with the water radical 氵 relates to liquids or fluids: 海 (sea), 池 (pond), 泳 (swim), 洗 (wash), 涙 (tears). Recognizing this pattern lets you make educated guesses about unfamiliar kanji.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Radical</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Example Kanji</th><th>Kanji Meanings</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>氵</td><td>Water</td><td>海, 池, 泳, 洗, 涙</td><td>Sea, pond, swim, wash, tears</td></tr>
      <tr><td>火 / 灬</td><td>Fire</td><td>焼, 煮, 熱, 燃, 照</td><td>Burn, boil, heat, blaze, shine</td></tr>
      <tr><td>木</td><td>Tree/Wood</td><td>林, 森, 板, 桜, 枝</td><td>Grove, forest, board, cherry, branch</td></tr>
      <tr><td>口</td><td>Mouth</td><td>吸, 味, 呼, 吹, 唱</td><td>Inhale, taste, call, blow, sing</td></tr>
      <tr><td>言 / 訁</td><td>Speech</td><td>話, 語, 説, 読, 訳</td><td>Talk, language, explain, read, translate</td></tr>
      <tr><td>心 / 忄</td><td>Heart/Mind</td><td>思, 感, 怒, 悲, 恋</td><td>Think, feel, anger, sadness, love</td></tr>
      <tr><td>手 / 扌</td><td>Hand</td><td>持, 打, 投, 押, 拾</td><td>Hold, hit, throw, push, pick up</td></tr>
      <tr><td>金 / 釒</td><td>Metal</td><td>銀, 鉄, 鋼, 針, 鏡</td><td>Silver, iron, steel, needle, mirror</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Decomposition in Practice</h3>
  <p>When you encounter a new kanji, break it into components immediately. Take 教 (teach): it combines 孝 (filial piety) and 攵 (strike/action). Teaching was traditionally seen as instilling respect through discipline. Take 休 (rest): person 人 leaning against a tree 木. Take 明 (bright): the sun 日 and moon 月 together create brightness. These decompositions make characters memorable and meaningful.</p>
  <p>Use our <a href="/japanese/tools/kanji-lookup/">Kanji Lookup</a> tool to explore the radical components of any kanji. Understanding the building blocks accelerates your learning dramatically — instead of memorizing 2,000 individual pictures, you are combining a smaller set of meaningful parts.</p>

  <h2 id="mnemonic-stories">Mnemonic Stories and Visual Association</h2>
  <p>Creating vivid, often absurd stories that connect a kanji's components to its meaning is one of the most powerful memorization techniques. The more outrageous the story, the better it sticks in memory. This method exploits how human memory works: we remember narratives and images far better than abstract symbols.</p>

  <h3>Crafting Effective Mnemonics</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Kanji</th><th>Components</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Mnemonic Story</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td style="font-size: 1.5rem;">森</td><td>木 + 木 + 木</td><td>Forest</td><td>Three trees together make a forest — simple and literal!</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-size: 1.5rem;">男</td><td>田 + 力</td><td>Man</td><td>A man uses his strength (力) to work in the rice field (田).</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-size: 1.5rem;">好</td><td>女 + 子</td><td>Good/Like</td><td>A woman (女) with her child (子) = something good (好).</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-size: 1.5rem;">岩</td><td>山 + 石</td><td>Rock/Cliff</td><td>A stone (石) on a mountain (山) = a massive rock.</td></tr>
      <tr><td style="font-size: 1.5rem;">鳴</td><td>口 + 鳥</td><td>Chirp/Ring</td><td>A bird (鳥) opens its mouth (口) to sing.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>The best mnemonics are personal. A story that connects to your own experience will be more memorable than a generic one. If you have a friend named Yuki, associate 雪 (snow, also read "yuki") with them. If you love coffee, connect 豆 (bean) to your morning ritual. Personal connections create stronger neural pathways.</p>

  <h2 id="spaced-repetition">Spaced Repetition: The Science of Retention</h2>
  <p>Spaced repetition is the most scientifically validated method for long-term memorization. The core principle is simple: review material at increasing intervals. If you remember a kanji correctly, wait longer before reviewing it next time. If you forget, review it again soon. This optimizes your study time by focusing effort on characters you are about to forget.</p>

  <!-- Forgetting Curve Visual -->
  <div style="max-width: 500px; margin: 24px auto;">
    <div style="font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 12px; text-align: center; color: #333;">Optimal Review Intervals (Spaced Repetition)</div>
    <div style="background: #e3f2fd; padding: 12px 16px; border-radius: 6px; margin: 6px 0; display: flex; justify-content: space-between; align-items: center;">
